data.title: Australia, Canada sign deal to promote, strengthen critical minerals cooperation
data.description:
Australia said on Saturday it signed an agreement with Canada to promote and strengthen bilateral cooperation and trade on critical minerals at the Group of Seven meeting of energy and environment ministers in Toronto.

Resources Minister Madeleine King said she and Canadian counterpart Tim Hodgson signed the joint declaration of intent on critical minerals collaboration, aimed at deepening the countries' partnership on critical minerals.

G7 countries, except Japan, are heavily or exclusively reliant on China for a range of materials from rare earth magnets to battery metals. Canada this week said it wanted to focus on working with G7 partners to secure critical mineral supply deals while hosting the two-day meeting.

“I look forward to working with Canada to build resilient supply chains that support innovation and economic growth," King said in a statement.

The agreement comes after Prime Minister Anthony Albanese in September met his Canadian counterpart in the United Kingdom for talks, including on critical minerals, according to government statements.

Australia and the U.S. last month agreed a wide-ranging critical minerals deal aimed at countering China's dominance in the sector.

data.title: White House Limits Reporters' Access to Communications Office — WSJ
data.description:
By Annie Linskey

WASHINGTON — The White House is imposing new restrictions on press access to the West Wing, limiting reporters' ability to enter the section where senior communications staff typically work.

Under new rules announced Friday evening, reporters will need an appointment with a senior official before they are allowed to enter the warren of offices where top White House press staff work, including the traditional office for the press secretary.

It means that reporters who regularly cover the White House will no longer be able to walk to the so-called "upper press" office suites, an area that is close to the Oval Office and can give reporters quick access to top officials for major breaking stories and routine developments. At times, the access can lead to chance meetings with other senior officials.

The decision follows a new policy the Pentagon imposed earlier this month on journalists who cover the armed services, seeking to restrict their communications with military sources. Those who refused to agree to the new rules had to forfeit their Pentagon press badges. The Wall Street Journal was among dozens of national news organizations that didn't agree to the new policy and lost access.

The White House "upper press" offices have been open for reporters during past administrations — including President Trump's first term.

But other White House officials have sought to restrict media movements. In the early 1990s, former President Bill Clinton's communications director, George Stephanopoulos, briefly enacted similar press restrictions, closing off areas where senior press officials work. The policy lasted about five months.

In the Friday announcement restricting press access, the White House cited changes it made in which White House communications staff now handle inquiries that used to be directed to press staff at the National Security Council.

Due to those changes, "members of the White House Communications Staff are routinely engaging with sensitive material," according to the memo that was issued by Communications Director Steven Cheung and press secretary Karoline Leavitt. "In order to protect such material, and maintain coordination between National Security Council Staff and White House Communications Staff, members of the press are no longer permitted to access Room 140 without prior approval."

Write to Annie Linskey at annie.linskey@wsj.com

data.title: Trump's Demands Throw Wrench Into Delicate Shutdown Talks — WSJ
data.description:
By Lindsay Wise, Brian Schwartz and Siobhan Hughes

WASHINGTON — President Trump's demand that Republican senators bypass Democrats to reopen the federal government risked upsetting delicate negotiations on Capitol Hill, where lawmakers were finally making progress toward a deal to end the monthlong impasse and head off more pain for American households.

Optimism had been growing among Republican and Democratic senators involved in talks over recent days, with hopes that a resolution could be reached in the week ahead, people familiar with discussions said.

But Trump's new demand in a social-media message late Thursday to eliminate the Senate filibuster rule could complicate the path forward. Meanwhile, food aid is at risk of lapsing for millions of people, the nation's airports are increasingly snarled, and Affordable Care Act health-plan enrollees are confronted with sharply higher premiums.

Trump has been frustrated with Democrats over the shutdown, and for weeks he has been considering the idea of eliminating the filibuster to try to expedite a reopening, according to a senior White House official. After returning from a weeklong trip to Asia, he finally "pulled the trigger" in the Truth Social post, the official said.

The filibuster rule requires most bills to get 60 votes to advance in the Senate, giving the minority party significant power to block or shape legislation. Since September, Senate Minority Leader Chuck Schumer (D., N.Y.) has demanded talks to extend expiring enhanced ACA subsidies before Democrats will provide the votes for a GOP bill to reopen the government. Republicans have a 53-47 majority, and so far, only three senators who caucus with Democrats have crossed the aisle in more than a dozen failed votes.

In remarks Friday on his way to Florida, Trump didn't mention his filibuster demand, but reiterated that he was willing to talk with Democrats if they would provide votes to reopen the government.

"Let them open up the country, and we'll meet," he said. "It's so easily solved."

A White House spokeswoman said that if Democrats don't work with Republicans to reopen the government, then the "nuclear option" of ending the filibuster will need to be used.

Trump's stance is at odds with that of many Senate Republicans. Senate Majority Leader John Thune (R., S.D.) has pledged to protect the longstanding rule, and a spokesman said Friday that his position hadn't changed.

Rising pressure

Recent days have been marked by flight delays across the country — including at Reagan National Airport, which held up senators' trips home Thursday. The delays were in part due to absenteeism among air-traffic controllers who have been working without pay.

Friday's disruptions to air travel were among the most widespread since the shutdown began. The Federal Aviation Administration issued ground delays for flights out of airports including those in New York, Boston, Dallas-Fort Worth and Houston. Federal officials have warned that the shutdown's impact on the aviation system could worsen over the weekend.

On Saturday, the lapse in funding for the Supplemental Nutrition Assistance Program serving more than 40 million lower-income and disabled people could start hitting households and the businesses where they shop. Money is also running out for an aid program for pregnant women and infants, as well as federally funded Headstart child-care centers.

While SNAP has enrollees in red and blue states, Democrats have been the fiercest defenders of the program. In his comments Friday, Trump cast it as largely a Democratic issue. "When you're talking about SNAP, if you look it's largely Democrats, they're hurting their own people," he said.

Democrats have charged that the Trump administration is withholding money from a contingency fund that could be used to fund SNAP. Agriculture Secretary Brooke Rollins said Friday that was "absolutely false," maintaining that the law doesn't allow the use of the fund during a shutdown — and wouldn't be sufficient to cover the full cost in any case.

On Friday, two federal judges said the Trump administration must use emergency funds to keep paying federal food-assistance benefits.

Unions and airline executives have urged Congress to pass Republicans' stopgap bill to reopen the government, putting more pressure on Democrats. Many government workers missed their first full paychecks in the past week, even as the administration has scraped together funds to keep troops paid.

This weekend also brings open enrollment for next year's ACA health coverage, and many consumers are facing sticker shock. Enhanced subsidies passed by Democrats during the Covid-19 pandemic are expiring at the end of the year. Republicans didn't extend the temporary subsidies in Trump's "big beautiful" tax-and-spending law.

New optimism on Capitol Hill

While lawmakers said any deal would take some time and wouldn't come before the weekend deadlines, there had been signs of progress Thursday, the last day of this past week's session.

"The conversations that I've been in with my colleagues, I think this week have been more productive than any other week so far," Sen. Catherine Cortez Masto (D., Nev.) said in an interview Thursday. "You're seeing both Democrats and Republicans feeling the impacts from their own constituents."

On Thursday, Sens. Jeanne Shaheen (D., N.H.), Angus King (I., Maine) and Maggie Hassan (D., N.H.) could be seen heading into Schumer's offices. After they left, they streamed into a basement hideaway, where Sens. Jacky Rosen (D., Nev.) and Gary Peters (D., Mich.) joined them. Peters and Shaheen are preparing to retire and are seen as being at the crux of any deal.

Thune expressed hope Thursday that the outcome of elections Tuesday would shake loose more members who might be willing to negotiate, describing them as a possible "inflection point" to reopen the government. Virginia and New Jersey have competitive governor races, while New York City is voting for mayor.

"Maybe that'll free some people up to be able to vote yes," he said.

Trump's call to end the filibuster puts Democrats in an awkward spot. When they were in the majority, they moved to weaken the rule, saying it grew out of past efforts to block civil-right laws. But defections kept them short of the 51 votes needed. Now, with Republicans in charge, Democrats are using the same rule to block the GOP.

House Minority Leader Hakeem Jeffries (D., N.Y.) said Friday on CNN that Republicans "don't work for the American people, they work for Donald Trump." He didn't weigh in on whether the Senate should keep the filibuster. "It is a Jim Crow relic, but ultimately it is their decision, " he said.

Support for the filibuster among Republican senators is widespread, but some have floated ideas to change or eliminate the rule to end the shutdown.

"If Democrats don't stop playing games, it's time to blow up the filibuster," Sen. Tommy Tuberville (R., Ala.) said on X.

Ending it now would clear the way for Republicans to reopen the government with a party-line vote, but it would dramatically reshape the way the Senate operates.

"The filibuster has traditionally been viewed as a very important safeguard," said House Speaker Mike Johnson (R., La.). "If the shoe was on the other foot, I don't think our team would like it."

Write to Lindsay Wise at lindsay.wise@wsj.com, Brian Schwartz at brian.schwartz@wsj.com and Siobhan Hughes at Siobhan.hughes@wsj.com

data.title: Drugmakers must face skincare drug price-fixing lawsuit, US judge rules
data.description:
By Jonathan Stempel

A federal judge on Friday said 36 drugmakers and executives must face nearly all claims in an antitrust lawsuit brought by most U.S. states, accusing them of conspiring to fix prices of 80 generic drugs.

Chief Judge Michael Shea of the federal district court in Connecticut rejected claims that 45 states, the District of Columbia and four U.S. territories waited an unreasonably long time to pursue federal antitrust claims, and missed formal deadlines to file similar claims under state laws.

Led by Connecticut, the states accused drugmakers including Pfizer , Perrigo and Sandoz of conspiring to raise prices, limit competition and allocate customers for drugs, primarily for skin ailments, between 2009 and 2016.

In a 130-page decision, Shea said the defendants failed to show that the states "lacked diligence" in pursuing their case, citing evidence that the defendants pursued "affirmative acts" to conceal their alleged collusion.

"A reasonable juror could find that the defendants' 'blaming supply,' making uncompetitively high bids, and falsely citing production costs for increased prices were aimed at concealing their alleged conspiracy," the Hartford-based judge wrote.

Lawyers for Pfizer, Perrigo and Sandoz did not immediately respond to requests for comment after market hours. A spokeswoman for Connecticut Attorney General William Tong did not immediately respond to a similar request.

Brand names of some products in the case included the acne medication Differin, anti-fungal medicine Lotrimin AF Cream, and Ritalin for attention deficit disorder and attention deficit hyperactivity disorder.

The case is Connecticut et al v. Sandoz Inc et al, U.S. District Court, District of Connecticut, No. 20-00802.

Several PayPal Holdings executives have recently sold shares of the company, according to SEC Form 4 filings. Natali Chris, VP and Chief Accounting Officer, and a 10% owner, sold 1,374 shares at a price of $69.1318 per share, totaling $94,987. Following the sale, Chris no longer directly owns any Common Stock in PayPal Holdings.

Suzan Kereere, President of Global Markets and a 10% owner, sold 5,000 shares at a weighted average price of $69.5244 per share, totaling $347,622. The sales prices ranged from $69.4750 to $69.6100. After the transaction, Kereere directly owns 43,483 shares of PayPal Holdings. This sale was executed under a Rule 10b5-1 plan adopted on March 7, 2025.

Diego Scotti, EVP, GM Consumer Group, and a 10% owner, sold 3,838 shares under a pre-arranged trading plan at weighted average prices ranging from $67.9500 to $70.2900, resulting in a total sale amount of $264,702. Following these transactions, Scotti directly owns 16,989 shares of PayPal Holdings. The sales were conducted pursuant to a Rule 10b5-1 trading plan adopted on March 7, 2025.
